{
  "result": "Some mornings I imagine a library that never really existed, yet feels more vivid than the rooms I inhabit. Sunlight wanders through high windows, painting maps on the dust, and every shelf hums like a muted orchestra tuning for something daring. When I stroll between the aisles I meet phantom mentors, people whose voices live only in margin notes and errant underlines. A mathematician whispers about elegant proofs while a botanist debates the patience of seeds, and suddenly the room smells of pine forests after rain. I borrow courage from their persistence. The shelves aren\u2019t organized by discipline; heartbreak sits beside thermodynamics, and comic timing flirts with epidemiology. This mess teaches me to treat curiosity like a compass rather than a leash. Every question becomes a door, and it\u2019s my job to knock even if I\u2019m unsure of the welcome. Sometimes the door opens onto a page of patient failures, experiments abandoned after years of tending. Those stories warn me that wonder is a marathon wearing the disguise of a sprint. Other times the door reveals an ecstatic note scribbled in pencil, the academic equivalent of fireworks. I pocket these sparks, carrying them outside where pragmatic daylight might otherwise flatten everything into errands and invoices. On the sidewalks, people hurry past, earbuds sealing them into private universes, yet I like to imagine the hidden footnotes trailing behind their footsteps. Maybe if we paused together we\u2019d exchange phrases, swap lenses, and discover that attention is the quietest, bravest rebellion we own.",
